File: President Cyril Ramaphosa Public Enterprises Minister Pravin Gordhan. JOHANNESBURG - Government will ask South African Airways (SAA) business rescue practitioners to review their announcement on cancelling unprofitable routes. All domestic routes except Cape Town were cancelled, as well as some regional and international routes. WATCH: Government does not agree with SAA decisions Public Enterprises Minister Pravin Gordhan says government will make representations to the practitioners. He says they need to balance trimming unprofitable routes with the need to ensure the sustainability of the airline. READ:Â SAA Express ordered to undergo business rescue Gordhan says the decisions have caused market and customer uncertainty that may jeopardise the long-term future of SAA. Aviation expert Guy Leitch says SAA must trim the fat if it wants to stay in the air. #DStv403 Aviation expert Guy Leitch says SAA must trim the fat if it wants to stay in the air. "It's like any other business, you have to get the fundamentals right. You have to get revenue up and overhead costs down. The process is reversed, revenue is being cut enormously because of these routes cuts and the desertion of passengers." The embattled airline is under business rescue and says it has no choice but to cut jobs and drop unprofitable routes. Years of corruption, mismanagement and state capture has bled billions out of the airline.